Technological determinism is a concept that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, from the technological incentive or technological imperative to the strict understanding that human fate is guided by a basic logic of scientific and technological manifestation.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: that the development of technology itself follows a path that is largely above cultural or political influence, and that technology in turn has “effects” on societies that are inherent, not socially conditioned.
For example, it can be said that the invention of the car necessarily leads to the development of roads.
However, a nationwide road network is not worth it for just a few cars so new production methods have been developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
Mass ownership of cars leads to more accidents on roads, leading to the discovery of new techniques in health care to treat injuries.
